ural institutions and businesses to hire talented and hardworking individuals, women, people of colour, and those from working class backgrounds are systematically disbarred.While the inequalities that characterise both workforce and audience remain unaddressed, the positive contribution culture makes to society can never be fully realised.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultural industriesxSocial aspects. 0aDiscrimination. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Classes & Economic Disparity.2bisacsh  aclass.  acultural and creative industries.  acultural consumption.  acultural production.  acultural work.  aculture.  agender.  ainequality.  arace.  asocial mobility.1 aBrook, Orian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Brien, Dave, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aO’Brien, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTaylor, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615215240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526152152423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526152152/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles